docs.abstract: Camae Ayewa makes a blend of hip-hop, spoken-word poetry, punk and electro as Moor Mother. In Irreversible Entanglements, she records scalding free jazz. Both have new albums this fall.
docs.snippet: Camae Ayewa makes a blend of hip-hop, spoken-word poetry, punk and electro as Moor Mother. In Irreversible Entanglements, she records scalding free jazz. Both have new albums this fall.
docs.lead_paragraph: The poet and musician Camae Ayewa is a study in nonstop movement. On a recent video call from Los Angeles, she chatted while pacing her apartment, stopping to open a few cabinets and pop a Ricola cough drop. “When people hang out with me, we’re not going to be just sitting down and talking the whole time,” she said. “I like creating. It’s my energy.”

headline.main: Moor Mother’s Musical Galaxy Grows Even Bigger
headline.print_headline: Her Musical Galaxy  Grows Even Bigger

docs.lead_paragraph: Police officials in Rochester, N.Y., said on Thursday that they had filed departmental charges against an officer who took part in arresting Daniel Prude, a Black man who died in March 2020 after the police pinned him face down on the ground and put a mesh hood over his head.

docs.snippet: Facebook called it “an unacceptable error.” The company has struggled with other issues related to race.
docs.lead_paragraph: Facebook users who recently watched a video from a British tabloid featuring Black men saw an automated prompt from the social network that asked if they would like to “keep seeing videos about Primates,” causing the company to investigate and disable the artificial intelligence-powered feature that pushed the message.

headline.main: Facebook Apologizes After A.I. Puts ‘Primates’ Label on Video of Black Men

docs.lead_paragraph: Shortly after the attacks of Sept. 11, an English teacher in central Washington State assigned her eighth and ninth graders to write poems based on the lead article in The Times. The teacher, Tammy Grubb, said her intention was to give the students a way to process their feelings. The poems were posted in the school hallway and then, since my byline was on the article, Ms. Grubb sent them to me, 77 of them.

headline.main: I Wrote the Lead Times Article on 9/11. Here’s What Still Grips Me.
headline.print_headline: I Wrote the Lead Times Article on 9/11. Here’s What Still Grips Me.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Fewer than 100 right-wing demonstrators, sharply outnumbered by an overwhelming police presence and even by reporters, gathered at the foot of the Capitol on Saturday to denounce what they called the mistreatment of “political prisoners” who had stormed the building on Jan. 6.
